-- Sub-Saharan Equities Report: Air Mauritius, Diamond Trust, First Bank Move
-- B y   V i n c e n t   N w a n m a   a n d   J o h n s t o n e   O l e   T u r a n a
-- 2010-11-11T14:32:04Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-11-11/sub-saharan-equities-report-air-mauritius-diamond-trust-first-bank-move.html
The  Nigerian Stock Exchange All-
Share Index  advanced to the highest since July 29, adding 1.9
percent to 25,894.42 by 12:34 p.m. in Lagos.  Mauritius’s  SEMDEX Index  rose for the third time in four
days, climbing 0.1 percent to 1,888.38 by the 1:30 p.m. close in
Port Louis. Kenya’s  All-Share Index  retreated 0.9 percent to
83.58 by the 3 p.m. close in Nairobi, the second drop in three
days. Namibia’s  FTSE/Namibia Overall Index  slipped 0.5 percent
to 848.76 by 3:56 p.m. in Windhoek, while the  Ghana Stock
Exchange All-Share Index  increased 0.2 percent to 6,818.6.  The following shares rose or fell in sub-Saharan Africa,
excluding South Africa. Stock symbols are in parentheses.  Air Mauritius Ltd.  (AML MP) climbed 0.3 rupee, or 2
percent, to 15.7 rupees, the highest since June 2009. Net income
for the second quarter through September climbed 83 percent to
4.96 million euros ($6.8 million), the company said in a
statement.  Diamond Trust Bank of Kenya Ltd.  (DTKL KN), a lender with
operations in five African nations, climbed for the first time
in seven days, adding 2 shillings, or 1.6 percent, to 128
shillings. Net income more than doubled to 1.8 billion shillings
($22.5 million) from 808.2 million shillings a year earlier, the
company said in an e-mailed statement to the Nairobi Stock
Exchange today.  First Bank of Nigeria Plc  (FIRSTBAN NL), the country’s
second-biggest lender by market value, rose to the highest in
more than three months, climbing 65 kobo, or the maximum daily
limit of 5 percent, to 13.65 naira. “Between now and the end of
the year, the stock price will reach at least 18 naira” on
speculation about the dividend for the year through December,
Eugene Ezenwa, chief operating officer of Lagos-based Spring
Stockbrokers Ltd., said by phone.  State Bank of Mauritius Ltd.  (SBM MP) increased 2 rupees,
or 2.3 percent, to 89 rupees, the highest since Aug. 27. The
Indian Ocean island nation said profit for the first quarter
through September rose 1.4 percent to 509.9 million rupees ($17
million) from a year earlier, according to a statement published
on the website of the Stock Exchange of Mauritius after the
market closed.  To contact the reporters on this story:
